nt-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">right aspirations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are realised </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">for the children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">who </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">live in children’s homes.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have highlighted </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">where we think the proposals could be strengthened further</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and where we believe even further change is needed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We welcome the opportunity to work collaboratively with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in implementing these changes and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are pleased that</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> together, Ofsted a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nd the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> are exploring more widely how regulation and inspection can contribute further to improving the experiences of children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are also working closely with our national consultative forum where providers and local authorities are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">represented.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">take our responsibility as part of the safety net that safeguards children </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and young people very seriously and want to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> drive weaker homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and poor care </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">out of the system</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> more quickly</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> We intend to raise the bar </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in terms of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the standards we </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">expect providers and local authorities to meet.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We believe that the current system of regulation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, national minimum standards and statutory guidance is unhelpful, particularly as the statutory guidance is only applicable to those homes that are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">operated by</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We note that the guidance was established at a time when residential children’s homes were predominantly provided by local authorities, but we are very concerned that such fundamental guidance does not apply as it should to privately pr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ovided homes who now operate almost two thirds of all residential children’s homes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">think that the current national minimum standards </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> not </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ambitious.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> We believe that the concept of minimum is outdated and that only good is good enough for all childr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">en and young people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, whether they are learners in schools or</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> children being looked after.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We believe in some areas the legislative framework that supports Ofsted in taking </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">action</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> against weaker homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">needs to be strengthened</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">for example, the power to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">suspen</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">d registration </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and through stronger and more robust disqualification processes. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have been supportive of our suggestions and are working </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">closely with us </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to identify solutions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are pleased that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">agree</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">d to st</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rengthen </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">powers to take action where homes are not meeting the needs of children and y</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">oung people.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> It is also helpful that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and Ofsted share the same goal of a more </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> legislative framework that moves away from the concept of ‘minimum</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’ standards and instead focuses on principles that homes must be able to meet or be subject to enforcement and the ultimate sanction of cancellation where they do not.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> We recognise that some of these changes are complex and hope that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> shares the same se</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nse of urgency in making all of these changes happen.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We have set out</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> here the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">background about the sector and Ofsted’s inspections and our views o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> proposals which mirror our response to the three current consultations. We have also set out our fu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">rther proposals that we believe could strengthen the safeguards for children and young people.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">The children’s h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">omes sector</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> and Ofsted inspection</span></h1><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted took over responsibility for the inspection of children’s homes in April 2007. There are currently </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">2,0</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">66</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> children’s homes in England and each </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> inspected a minimum of twice per year. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">74% of these homes are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">operated</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> by the private or voluntary sector and 26% by local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">16 a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">re secure children’s homes and 5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">% are residential special schools</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that must register as children’s homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">because</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> they provide more than 295 days overnight care per year</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children’s homes ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> improved steadily over the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">past four years under the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">inspection </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">framework that ended in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">March 2011.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Over that time</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the proportio</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">outstanding </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">trebled to 17% </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the pr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">oportion </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">judged as</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> inadequate fell from </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">11% to 3%.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In April 2011</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">introduced a new inspection</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">framework</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> with a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">n explicit </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">focus on the experiences of children and young people. We have continued</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to revise and refine our approach to set a tougher and higher bar for providers and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">continue to raise expectations for providers. At the end of the first year of the new framework (April 2011-March 2012) the grade profile was 16% outstanding, 56% good,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> 23% adequate and 5% inadequate. The grade profile for April 2013 to August 2013 is 8% outstanding, 55% good, 29% adequate and 8% inadequate. The data cannot be simply interpreted as representing a sector that is in decline, although that may be the case f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">or some homes, but </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">overall it </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">must be seen in the context of a continual raising of expectations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">While </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted’s inspection framework for children’s homes reflects the requirements in the Children's Homes Regulations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">2001 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and the National Minimum Standards</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (NMS)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> we have continued to set a standard for good and outstanding care that exceeds these minimum requirements. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Since</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">2011, we have moved from a compliance model of inspection to an inspection that focuses more closely on the experiences and progress of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> children and young people. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Our reports reflect this change and in our surveys with placing social workers and commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the majority re</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">port</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ed that our </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">inspection reports have had a stronger focus on outcomes for children </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the progress they make an</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">reports influence their placement decisions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Improving inspection</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and taking action where provision is weak</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We have continued to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">raise the bar</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ith homes judged inadequate. In July this year </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">made it clear that in every case: </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Where a home is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> judged inadequate for overall effectiveness, the home will not have an interim inspection to check on progress</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> instead it will have a full inspection within six to eight weeks.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">If, at the second full inspection, the home is judged inadequate for overall </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">effectiveness, we will seek to cancel registration.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Where there has been a registered manager vacancy of 26 weeks or more, or where the vacancy has an impact on the welfare of the children, this will lead to a judgement of inadequate for leadership and man</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">agement. </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Where</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">leadership and management is judged inadequate, the overall judgement is likely to be inadequate.</span></li></ul><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are also subjecting those home</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that are judged inadequate to much closer monitoring and scrutiny</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> undertaking weekly visits if we consider this is appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and publishing monitoring reports of those visits from December 2013.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We know that inspection judgements make a difference. There has been a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">steep increase in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">closures</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> over the last few years. T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he number of children’s homes closed following an inadequate Ofsted inspection judgement in 2011-12 was 22; in 2012-13 it was 41. There have been 1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> resignations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of registration </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">following an inadequate judgement since April this year.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are taking more ac</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">tion to cancel and to restrict accommodation in those homes where we are not satisfied that children and young people are safe. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We believe we could take more action if the requirements of government guidance were more rigorous, were applicable to the entir</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e sector and if we had our ability to take enforcement action strengthened. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We have asked for this to be considered and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> believe that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> regulations that focus on children’s experiences and a stronger link between regulations and underpinning stan</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">dards will support Ofsted in taking action against those homes that do not strive for improvement and do not offer children and young people the best possible experiences.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We will continue to keep our inspection framework under close scrutiny and where we </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">identify areas for improvement, as we did in July, we will implement these changes. Irrespective of the time line established by the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> for the legislative changes, we will introduce a new inspection framework in April 2014 which will include a judgement </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of ‘requires improvement’. Our clear indication to the sector </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">that ‘good’ is the benchmark for our most vulnerable children.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Whether the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Department for Education’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> proposed reforms to the regulation of residential children’s homes are appropriate and sufficient</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> focus on strengthening regulations and guidance to drive improvement in the care of our most vulnerable children and make children’s ho</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">mes duties for safeguarding children much more explicit. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We welcome greater clarity about the responsibilities </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of owners and managers of homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to safeguard children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">regulation 11</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> had made the suggestion to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that this reg</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ulation should be strengthened. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e believe this will be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> more</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> helpful in enabling Ofsted to hold those homes to account where there is a failure to safe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">guard children and young people;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> for example, through inadequate responses to children and young people w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ho are missing. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">However, this needs to be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> seen in the context of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the wider review of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> requirements for provider</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">linked to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">more robust powers for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted to enforce. </span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Children placed out of authority</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> area</span></h3><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We think that accountabilities </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">those children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> placed out of authority are becoming much clearer and much more robust. </span></li><li style="font-fami