ont-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">However, this must not detract from the responsibilities </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of placing authorities </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">through the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Care Planning, Placement and Case Review (England) Regulations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">2010</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and we would still expect them to be meeting their duties to notify host authorities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> before ma</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">king a placement so that the health, education and specialist needs of children moving into the area can be met</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> welcome the suggested amendments</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to these regulations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> enhance information-sharing between placing authorities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Findings from </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">our recent thematic inspection of arrangements for looked after children placed out of area confirm the previous evidence that the notifications system is flawed and unreliable. This leads to an absence of, or at the very least a risk of delay</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the prov</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ision of necessary</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> health, education, protection</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and support for vulnerable children living away from home. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Strategic needs assessments for ‘receiving’ local authorities are persistently undermined by inaccurate information. We suggest that greater emphas</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is could be placed upon the requirement for local authorities to notify the host authority when a child leaves that area, so that this information could be kept up-to-date</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> providing the host authority with clearer sense of the stretch on local resource and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> making notification conversations more meaningful in terms of what can be expected for a child coming into the area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">welcome any</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> proposal</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> strengthen the accountability and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> oversight of corporate parents and increase consistency of decision-making for looked after children. We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">very much welcome the proposal that before making any such decision</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to place a child out of their local authority areas,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">irector of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">hi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ldren’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ervices</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> must be satisfied that suitable arrangements are in place to safeguard and protect children. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We have in a number of discussions with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> suggested that the arrangements for this increased oversight should be realistic in terms of the workl</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">oad of the senior team. We recommend therefore that in order for the management oversight to add real value, the detail is carefully considered in guidance about care and placement for children who may live away from their home area. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tah