be aware of the I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ndependent </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">viewing </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">fficer</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’s view before approving an out </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> area placement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We think th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">at when considering what is an out of authority area placement th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is decision should </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">not be based on mileage or travelling time but should take into account </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the specific needs of t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he child to be near to their placing authority and to their families where the plan is to reunify them. Of particular importance is that their education, health and relationship</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> with other important adults </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> not compromised without good and proper consi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">derations that the child understands. Wh</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ere a child is placed within a region of co-terminus</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> authorities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> where information is shared and resources are pooled, they would be deemed to be in a local placement</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> provided their schooling and need for contact wit</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">h their families remains intact.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Emerging findings from Ofsted’s recent thematic inspection evaluating arrangements for looked after children living out of area (report to be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">published in late 2013) suggest</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that children who live out of area but in a neighbouring authority can often benefit from pre-existing close collaboration between agencies, or from continuing services from the home authority. As the proposal document suggests, many looked after children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> living within a large local authority can be further from their home community than other looked after children from the same area living in an adjacent authority.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We think it is right that area authorities must be consulted before a Director of Children’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s Services can approve a decision to place a child in that authority area. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma