ment’. The hea</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ding ‘before a looked after child runs away’ appears to suggest that this is a likely outcome. A more positive heading to this section would be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> ‘minimising the risks and supporting stability.’ Where reference is made to ‘listening to children’, it is also</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> important to reference the need to either act upon children’s views or</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> where this is not possible, ensure they are helped to understand why this is the case. W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e wondered whether paragraph 64</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in the documentation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">should reference the requirement for sign </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">off of out of authority placements at the most senior level</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in a local authority</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">When a looked after child</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">who has been missing </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">found, it would be helpful to be more prescriptive about the importance of a statutory review. In our opinion, in all insta</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nces a statutory review should be considered to decide whether the placement is still suitable </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and safe </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and to create/update a risk management plan. Where it is decided not to hold a review</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the reasons for the decision should be recorded</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and a recorded di</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">scussion with the responsible social worker for the child must be in evidence</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. As a minimum we believe that the independent reviewing officer </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">(IRO) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">should be fully informed and it is their responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">along with the statutory allocated social worker </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">determine whether an early review should take place.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Our thematic survey indicated that where practice is poor in relation to children who go missing, professionals tended to focus on each individual episode as a stand-alone</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> event</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. There was little evidenc</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e that local authorities were either</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> a) looking at individual children’s behaviour on a long-term basis to try to understand why the young person was running away</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> or b) using the information on all children who ran away to build up a picture of issues fo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r the area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> or the residential provision</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The latter is important if local authorities are to understand the needs of their </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">children, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">provide services appropriately and understand whether the services they provide are making a difference. The former is imp</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ortant because it feeds into the idea that these are ‘problem teenagers’ with ‘challenging and risk taking behaviour’. The thematic inspection in line with our serious case review report ‘Ages of Concern’ found this to be common – the services, and the pro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">fessionals, became focused on the behaviour as the primary issue, trying to manage and contain it, trying to make sure that young people were safe when they ran away, but with no attempt to interpret the behaviour as a manifestation of any underlying issue</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s. Thus the problem becomes orientated with the young person and little or no attempt is made to really understand the young person and their emotional needs. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We would welcome clearer signposting of the need for risk management plans that are overseen by </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the allocated social worker and the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ndependent Reviewing Officer (IRO)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. In a number of places in the guidance the role of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">IRO</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> could be strengthened. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We welcome the clear messages about compiling and sharing data in relation to missing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> children and yo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ung people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. Reference to how this information can be used in identifying risks that then influence the licensing of premises and businesses would be helpful.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We welcome the clear distinction made between safe and well checks and return home interviews and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">think that this could be strengthened by a stronger emphasis on the importance of the professionals that undertake these tasks </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">record and shar</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the outcomes appropriately and effectively with other involved professionals to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">improve the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">child</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ren and young people.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We would like to see greater emphasis on the responsibility of corporate parents, as well as</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Local Safeguarding Children Board (LSCB)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Director of Children’s Services (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DCS</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, to scrutinise practice closely in order to safeguard </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">looked after children and to ensure that they take account the views of children when assuring themselves that practice is good, including proper analysis of lessons from safe and well checks and return interviews</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">proposals are generally silent </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the role of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">LSCB throughout the proposals. We would welcome a reflection on what, if any</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> role the LSCB should have in knowing and understanding what is happening in their local children’s homes so that they can monitor and evaluate the effectivenes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s of the local arrangements to safeguard these children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We would also like to see further consideration given to the current statutory guidance around restriction of liberty and clearer principles for children’s homes and foster carers ab</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">out expectations to keep children and young people safe balanced with not restricting their liberty. It is clear from our inspection activity and investigation of complaints that providers of social care are confused and unclear how to interpret current go</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">vernment guidance.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We also think that the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> should work closely with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Department of Health</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that provide</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s are clear that the guidance on ‘Guidance on permissible forms of control in residential care’ is no longer current.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> It is still widely available on the internet yet it is out of date and conflicts with other guidance.</span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Child sexual exploitation</span></h3><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">We really welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> intention to remove references to ‘prostitution’ from regulation and had already approached the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> about making this change. It is critical to acknowledge that these children and young people are victims and not willing adult agents.</span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Where homes are situated</span></h3><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">While we agree with the proposal that the registered person should conduct an annual assessment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">any risks resulting from the area where a children’s home is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">operating</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, we think that further clarification is needed. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The final regulations need to be absolutely clear who must undertake this annual assessment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and the criteria that are to be deployed </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">to make such an assessment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. As with all risk assessments we would also expect the registered person to undertake such a risk assessment more regularly if any information indicated this would be appropriate. The regulation would be more powerful if it requi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">red the registered person to take action to mitigate the risks identified</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> as well as being required to discuss those risks with the placing and host authorities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. It is unclear in the current proposals whether there will be a requirement for this risk asses</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">sment to be shared with Ofsted on an annual basis</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and what action Ofsted might take if the assessment is poor or unconvincing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">For those homes already registered, there needs to be greater clarity </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">about </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">how </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">new</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">requirement</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">will be introduced</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> what action they are expected to take</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and what powers Ofsted will have to take action against homes where their circumstance changes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Where the local police or children’s services have concerns abou</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t the site of a children’s home</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, it is unclear what, if a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ny, action Ofsted can take and how this relates to powers of refusal or cancellation. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The planning authority should have a role in disclosing the homes that are already located in the area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and in deciding the viability of applications for new provision in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the same area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We agree that proposed children’s homes must take account of the local area before they submit an application to Ofsted. We are less clear how this risk assessment, in itself, can provide grounds for refusal and more particularly evidence o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">f the standard that a registered homes tribunal would accept. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t is unclear to Ofsted what account they can take of the views of other agencies if homes believe they can mitigate those risks. A likely area of contention will be the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">siting</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> of other children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’s homes in the vicinity which will immediately introduce Ofsted into assessing what in effect are commercially competitive decisions. Our clear view on the clustering of children’s homes in a local </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> is that this must be a decision for the planning aut</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">hority to influence not Ofsted. Local authorities are responsible for their local areas and decisions about the nature and volume of businesses that are acceptable locally, exemplified recently by the number of betting shops permissible in a London Borough</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. Ofsted cannot and should not be asked to make these decisions but rather confirm on application for registration, that the applicant has sought the necessary local consent. </span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> and professional development of managers and staff</span></h3><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">A well trained</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> workforce is critical to the wider aspirations for vulnerable children and young people. Where all care staff working in a children’s home have not attained the necessary qualifications within two years of starting work, then Ofsted will be able to take a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ction against the registered provider for a failure to meet regulations.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> The bar that is being set by the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> does not feel </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and does not suggest that we will bring the most qualified workforce to work with children and young people with comple</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">x and diverse needs. It is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in our view, not a high enough bar. In addition there should be a test of experience as well as qualification and a strengthened requirement for this detail to be set out in professional references about employees who work with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">children in residential care. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">While we understand that there need to be transitional arrangements in place</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> we are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">concerned that without </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a properly </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">qualified workforce</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the wider intentions of the regulatory reform programme will have less impact than desired for children and young people. We would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">strongly urge the government to set an </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">earlier commencement date for the new qualification requirements for registered manag</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ers in Regulation 8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and consider that 2016 is appropriate. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As the consultation outlines, these are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">critical </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">leadership posts</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and they make a fundamental difference to the quality of care provided to children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. We welcome the change to Regulation 8 (Fitness </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">of Manager) to make it clear that managers without the necessary qualification will not be eligible for registration. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Again we consider the cut off of 2018 too long and suggest that this aspect takes effect within 12 months. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We would</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in any event,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> further discussion on how these new requirements should be applied retrospectively to those registered managers currently in post and to current registered managers who move </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to new registered manager </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">pos</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">itions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We also welcome </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the change </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">that registered m</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">anagers </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">who are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">seeking to continue managing a children’s home must be able to provide documentary evidence that they have completed relevant “continuing professional development” (CPD). We are less clear how this applies to managers who may have been regi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">stered for a number of years and how they should interpret the new qualification requirements if they remain in their current post. </span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Leadership and management</span></h3><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are already engaged in detailed discussions with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in relation to portability of registered </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">manager status and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">we welcome the on-going discussion about how we can best enable high quality management oversight in children’s homes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, including a resolution regarding the smaller homes where a registered manager is shared between two registered service</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We know the importance of stro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ng leadership and management and the failings that can occur where this is not in place. We have recently (July) amended our inspection framework so that where a home is without a manager for 26 weeks then the leadership an</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">d management judgement is likely to be inadequate and this will usually lead to an overall judgement of inadequate. Any ability to regulate against this failure would be welcomed, particularly an ability to hold the registered person accountable for the fa</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ilure to have a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">registered manager</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> in post as opposed to the current anomaly in the regulations which only refers to a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">manager</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> in post.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Our strong view is that it should not be possible for the most vulnerable children to be in the care of a home where there is not an appropriately skilled, qualified, experienced and ‘fit’ manager in post. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">think</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> that HMCI should be informed and an appl</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ication submitted within 21 days of appointment.</span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Monitoring of practice</span></h3><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">While we welcome the opportunity to strengthen the impact and rigour of regulation 33 monitoring, there is a concern that where the requirements of local authorities differ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> this may l</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ead to inconsistency in practice that is difficult for Ofsted to monitor and benchmark without clear cr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">iteria </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">about</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> what ‘approval’ means:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> whether this relates to individual approval, whether this is to be reviewed, and where this will </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">be located </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in the lo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cal authority functions. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and experience of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">independent </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">visitor are critical. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We do not agree with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> that the approval of independent visitor schemes should lie with the local authority. Their first duty is to ensure that the s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ocial worker responsible for the children in the care of the home visits and appraises the quality of care afforded to the children for whom it is the corporate parent. Whilst the independence of the visitors is critical and should be approved, it is not i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">n our view one of the functions of the host local authority and would involve them in resourcing checks and balances that are not their responsibility. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">This may be more of an onerous task for those local authorities with high concentrations of children’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">homes within their area and it is unclear who </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the final arbi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ter</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> of independence is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We do think that there is a level of tension in the ‘independence’ of the visitor where they are commissioned and funded by the registered provider for their services. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">This clearly creates a level of tension but that same tension exists currently for local authorities who resource independent chairs of the safeguarding children board and there will be other similar examples. The key issue must be that the provider has in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> place transparent and effective arrangements that set out how the independent evidence and reports of visitors under this regulation are managed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and in particular </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">actioned</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> where the reports are critical or indicate that improvement is required. Ofsted s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">crutinises these reports</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and will include in the report</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> any concerns about the independence of visitors or an absence of action where they report concerns.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We have suggested to the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">that they </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">may want to consider whether there should be any lay scrutin</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">y of practice in children’s homes. We will be most concerned with the quality and impact of the monitoring. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The views of children and young people about the quality of their experience are critical and must form part of any evaluation by an independent vi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">sitor. However</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e think it is difficult to ask children and young people for their views on the safeguarding arrangements and it may be better to consider how well staff respond to children’s concerns, the quality of relationships between children and sta</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ff and the level of concern children voice about their welfare. We would also want the independent visitor to review the response to complaints from children and young people and any complaints from the local community, including documenting the extent of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">change and improvement following the complaint</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We are unclear why the host authority would only receive the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">independent visitor’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">report on request</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">f this is about strengthening the safeguards for children and young people in the local area they live </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">then the host authority and/or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">LSCB</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> should have an interest in the quality of care children and young people experience.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">We think that the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">list of matters to be monitored by the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">registered person is comprehensive. Where the registered person is requi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">red to monitor safeguarding concerns, we would hope that this would include reviewing any referrals to children’s social care and/or the Local Authority Designated Officer, the quality of these referrals, any incidents that have not been referred that shou</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">ld have been and a role in escalating any issues where there is any concern about the response of the local authority, including where there is an unsatisfactory response to the need for a placement review.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">In addition we think that the registered person should monitor the quality of the relationships and communication with local authorities to ensure effective action is taken wherever there are shortfalls in the local authority responses and care of children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> and young people living at the home. </span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The statement of purpose</span></h3><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We are unclear </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">whether </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> have taken into account that a requirement for homes to publish the statement of purpose on their website may inadvertently mean that the address of the children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’s home is available to the wider public. If this were the intention, then our strong and unequivocal view is that this would compromise the safety of children and place them at risk of harm or further harm and we would not support this change. If publicat</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ion is to enable placing authorities to consider the resource on offer and no address is available, then we would support this change.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">support</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> proposals to improve the statement of purpose </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">but suggest that they </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">miss an opportunity to clearly </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">set out how health services will be made available, how they will be accessed and what specific services will be available, including the age range of children and young people looked after by the home.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We would also welcome inclusion of a statement about </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">children’s rights including how they can complain, the responses they should expect and how anti-discriminatory practice will be promoted in the home.</span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Accountability</span></h3><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">agree in principle with th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> proposal </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to include the details of the home’s registered pr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ovider and responsible individual in reports </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and would welcome further discussion with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> about the circumstances where they consider it may jeopardise the welfare of individual children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Further safeguards</span></h3><ol start="70" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Although Ofsted considers that an early revi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ew should be convened when a child is at risk where they live</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">think</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that the decision to do so should remain the responsibility of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">allocated social worker in concert with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">IRO. It is likely that any decisions not to convene a review if concerns </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have been expressed should be the exception</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Reasons for not convening a review following a request from any, or all, of the above parties (and, indeed, for deciding to convene an early review) should be recorded clearly and shared promptly with all releva</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">nt people, including the DCS.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> The views of parents, carers and managers of residential care homes should</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> however</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> be taken seriously and reasons given where a review is not convened. These should be made in writing. When a child requests a formal review (not currently included and we believe should be), the request should be accepted every time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We agree</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that safeguarding issues should be addressed as a specific requirement at each statutory review. This proposal is consistent with the finding in Ofsted’s recent thematic inspection report, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Independent reviewing officers; taking up the challenge? </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">(2013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">), t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">hat</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">some reviews did not address key issues (such as missing episodes) with sufficient detail, rigour or challenge.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We welcome </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">proposal that Directors of Children’s Services should approve and sign off the pathway plans for voluntarily accommodated 16 and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> 17 year olds whenever there is a proposal for them to leave care</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">. We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">believe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> this</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> should strengthen accountability of senior corporate parents for the quality of support </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and the suitability and quality of accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">provided to looked a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">fter children an</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">d care leavers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt">Whether the reforms are likely to prove effective or further measures are needed</span></p><h1 style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><ol start="73" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">e are pleased at the level of scrutiny and attention that is being applied by the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">programme of regu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">latory reform of which these proposals are a small part and we look forward to continuing to work collaboratively with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">through wider changes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Ofsted has been in discussion </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">about </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">a range of measures that we think would further improve the quality of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the experience of children and young people who live in children’s homes. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> understand and agree with our proposals and are exploring the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">possible</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> legislative vehicles to implement </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, with more complexity in some areas than others. We are sure that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> will wish to make their own comment on these complexities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">have asked </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to revisit the means and legalities around those persons that may be disqualified from working in children’s homes. Currently the legislation lacks the rigour and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">direct link with other parts of the legislation. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> are in agreement and looking to make the necessary changes. We t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">hink it is important that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">we take all measure</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> we can to ensure that unsuitable people are not able to be involved in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">operating</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> children’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">homes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We have also asked </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to consider increasing Ofsted’s powers. We currently have the power to restrict accommodation but we do not have the power to suspend the operation of a home. While we envisage that our use of this power would be exception</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> there are scenarios where it would be preferable for Ofsted to be able to take this significant step.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">There are three main Government frameworks that are applicable to children’s homes: </span></li></ol><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the regulations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">- applicable to all providers and subject to curr</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ent consultation. Ofsted can require all providers to meet regulations and take enforcement action where they do not;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the statutory guidance</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">- only applicable to local authorities and local authority children’s home</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. Ofsted can only make recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">against this guidance and has no power to take any action if a home fails to take these recommendations into account;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the national minimum standards</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">- these are applicable to all children’s homes and provide the guidance to the regulations. Ofsted can onl</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">y recommend that providers take account of the NMS unless there is an underpinning regulation to the specific issue.</span></li></ul><ol start="78" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Our view is that the current statutory guidance should </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">act </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">as a minimum safeguard, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">be applicable to all homes although we recognise there i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s no easy mechanism for that to be the case. We think that the concept of ‘minimum’ is outdated and would prefer to see a more </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> framework from government of what we should expect for children and young people.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We would also wish to have greater</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> powers to take action against those providers that are not achieving the best for children and young people. We intend to move from our current judgement scale of adequate to ‘requires improvement’ from April </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">2014</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. However </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and however high we</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> raise the bar in inspection</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> without the ability to take action where providers do not share these aspirations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> our ability to effect change is diminished. We want to be able to take robust action against those providers that fail to make improvement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">would maintain that the proposed changes need to be viewed as improving the quality of experiences for all looked after children, wherever they live and as such the changes should be taken into account within the fostering regulations. We would also like t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">o say the same overall </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> framework</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> we are discussing with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> applie</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> for those children and young people who live</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> with foster families. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> All data in this report is correct at 17 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Missing children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> (120364), Ofsted, 2013; </span><a href="http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/resources/missing-children"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.ofsted.gov.u</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">k</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">/resources/120364</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Missing children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> (120364), Ofsted, 2013; </span><a href="http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/resources/missing-children"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.ofsted.gov.uk/resource</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">s</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">/120364</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">LAC (93)13: Guidance on permissible forms of control in children's residential care</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">, Department of Health, 1993; </span><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/+/www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publicationsandstatistics/Lettersandcirculars/LocalAuthorityCirculars/AllLocalAuthority/DH_4003969"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family: